is far from a truthful depiction. Members of Sufi communities have worked as resistance fighters, aid workers, business people, actors, professors, and daily workers in creative and ingenious ways to keep and renew their networks of community support. Based on long-term ethnographic field research among multiple Sufi communities in different urban areas of Afghanistan, the book examines navigational strategies employed by Sufi leaders over the past four decades to weather periods of instability and persecution, showing how they adapted to changing conditions in novel ways that crafted Sufism as a force in the civil sphere. This book offers a rare on-the-ground view into how Sufi leaders react to moments of transition within a highly insecure environment, and how humanity shines through the darkness during times of turmoil.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslam and statezAfghanistan2DLC. 0aIslam and statezAfghanistan. 0aMuslim religious leaderszAfghanistan2DLC. 0aMuslim religious leaderszAfghanistan. 0aSufismxPolitical aspectszAfghanistan2DLC. 0aSufismxPolitical aspectszAfghanistan. 7aHISTORY / Military / Afghan War (2001-).2bisacsh  aAfghanistan.  aAuthority/Leadership.  aCivil Society.  aEthnography.  aIslam.  aMinority.  aPluralism.  aSocial Navigation.  aSufism.  aWar/Conflict.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363754240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637542423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637542/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles